An $n \times n \times n$ cube is composed of $n^{3}$ unit cubes. Each unit cube is painted with one color. For each $n \times n \times 1$ box consisting of $n^{2}$ unit cubes (of any of the three possible orientations), we consider the set of the colors present in that box (each color is listed only once). This way, we get $3 n$ sets of colors, split into three groups according to the orientation. It happens that for every set in any group, the same set appears in both of the other groups.
